Alternative metrics to predict Foreground spectral index variations¶

Giuseppe Puglisi (Stanford) - 10/31/2019

Recently there has been mail offline discussions about building up a recipe in order to choose where best to observe and avoid foregrounds.

The common figures of merit used so far have been polarization amplitude (post ) and the $r$-equivalent maps (post )

In this post, I present a different methodology which might be more data driven than the metrics adopted so far. In particular, I've focused on Clustering methodologies, to alternatively define and identify patches accordingly to spectral index variations. Clustering techniques can be used for this goal, since they group data instances into subsets in such a manner that similar instances are grouped together, while different instances belong to different groups (or clusters). To quantify how similar or close two instance are, a similarity measure ( or equivalently distance metric ) needs to be define accordingly to the type of data we use.

There is a large variety of clustering methods as well as distances in the literature (e.g. the documentation page of scikit-learn) , I've tested a couple of them and found that Hierarchical Clustering does the best job. The Hierarchical clustering (see more details in VanderPlas et al. sect.IV ) is mostly adopted to finds clusters at all scales and can be approached as an agglomerative (bottom-up) procedure, all clusters are built by progressively merging nearest pairs.

Here I present preliminary results applying the Hierarchical Clustering to $\beta_d$ maps from the PySM template and from the GNILC Planck release.

Map-preprocessing¶

  • Convolve maps with a $6 $ deg beam and rotate them from Galactic to Equatorial
  • Degrade maps at nside=32

Similarity for Planck Maps¶

When dealing with Planck maps, uncertainties need to be taken into account in defining the similarity between two pixels. Assuming that each value of $\beta_d$ is normal distributed with $\sigma= \sigma(\beta_d)$ we can estimate the continuous probability distribution, $ \mathcal{P} \sim N( {\beta }_d ,\sigma(\beta_d))$ for every pixel in the map. We then use the Hellinger distance to quantify the affinity between two probability distributions. (It essentially estimates the overlapping area of two Normal distributions, if perfectly overlaps the two pixels are defined similar. Any better metric ? )

Similarity for PySM maps¶

In case we don't have access to the uncertainties for $\beta_d$, we can simply use the Euclidean distance.

Spatial similarity¶

We can also impose a spatial similarity ( if two pixel coordinates are close ). Typical geodesic distance in the sphere is the Haversine distance.

What is the optimal number of clusters ?¶

We iterate on several choices of $K$, i.e. the number of clusters to seek for an optimal value $K_{opt}$ of clusters. $K_{opt}$ is commonly evaluated using the validity index method (see ref) defined where both the under and over-partition measures have small values. The former has very small values for $K\geq K_{opt}$ and large values for $K< K_{opt}$, whereas the latter shows the opposite behavior, relatively small values for $K< K_{opt}$ and large values vice versa.

Fig1 (blue) Under and (orange) over- partition measures estimated for several choice of $K$. Notice that the sum of the two combined presents a minimum at around $K \approx 20$, we choose this value to be the optimal number of clusters for the PySM map.
